e district, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Westmill, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Sandy, Central Bedfordshire, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Central Bedfordshire, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hessett, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Hessett, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1523–7 June 1557":"1523–7 June 1557","1523–1557":"1523–1557","1529–Female":"1529–Deceased","1549–1630":"1549–1630","1560–1611":"1560–1611","1500–1543":"1500–1543","1500–Female":"1500–Deceased","1560":"1560","1546":"1546","1557":"1557","1523":"1523","1611":"1611","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1630":"1630","1 January 1549":"1 January 1549","June 1557":"June 1557","7 June 1557":"7 June 1557","1529":"1529","1549":"1549","Westmill, East Hertfordshire district, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Westmill, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Sandy, Central Bedfordshire, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Central Bedfordshire, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Hessett, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Hessett, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richardson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Richard   + <i>-son</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. Compare   Ritson  .","Americanized form (and a Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Richardsson</b> or <b>Rikardsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Richard  , <i>Rikard</i>.","Americanized form of Norwegian and Danish <b>Richardsen</b> or Norwegian <b>Rikardsen</b>, cognates of 2 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Richarson","meanings":["English: variant of   Richardson  ."]},{"name":"Richerson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Richardson   or perhaps a patronymic from   Richer  ."]},{"name":"Richard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Jacques, Andre, Marcel, Pierre, Leonce, Normand, Camille, Lucien, Gilles, Henri.","English, French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, and Dutch: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The Middle English forms were <i>Richard</i> and <i>Rikard</i>, respectively Parisian Old French and Old Picard pronunciations of the ancient Germanic name. Middle English <i>Rikard</i> gives rise to the pet form   Rick  , whilst <i>Richard</i> has given the pet forms   Richie   and   Rich  . Both produced rhyming pet forms,   Dick   and   Hick   for <i>Rikard</i> and   Hitch   for <i>Richard</i>.","History: The LA Richard families are mainly descended from Acadian refugees in the second half of the 18th century. — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Richeson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Richardson  , but compare   Richerson  ."]},{"name":"Ritson","meanings":["English:","variant of <b>Richson</b>, a shortened form of   Richardson  . The name may sometimes have been confused with or assimilated to   Rushton  .","in southern England perhaps a habitational name from Ritson, in Halwell (Devon)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Richardson was born in 1523, in Hessett, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Thomas Richardson, was 23 and his mother, Mrs Thomas Richardson, was 24. He married Clare Convers in 1546, in Bedfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 7 June 1557, in Central Bedfordshire, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 34."},"et":{"1523–7 June 1557":"1523–7. juuni 1557","1523–1557":"1523–1557","1529–Female":"1529–Surnud","1549–1630":"1549–1630","1560–1611":"1560–1611","1500–1543":"1500–1543","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1560":"1560","1546":"1546","1557":"1557","1523":"1523","1611":"1611","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1630":"1630","1 January 1549":"1. jaanuar 1549","June 1557":"juuni 1557","7 June 1557":"7. juuni 1557","1529":"1529","1549":"1549","Westmill, East Hertfordshire district, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Westmill, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bedfordshire, England":"Bedfordshire, England","Sandy, Central Bedfordshire, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Central Bedfordshire, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hessett, Mid Suffolk district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Hessett, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1523–7 June 1557":"1523–7. kesäkuuta 1557","1523–1557":"1523–1557","1529–Female":"1529–Kuollut","1549–1630":"1549–1630","1560–1611":"1560–1611","1500–1543":"1500–1543","1500–Female":"1500–Kuollut","1560":"1560","1546":"1546","1557":"1557","1523":"1523","1611":"1611","1500":"1500","1543":"1543","1630":"1630","1 Janu